comments: I'm really, really wary of the results of a study like this. These ahistorical, decontextualized situations, presented in questionnaire form, probably prove nothing about how we act in real life, where emotion and time are factors. It is easy to coldly and theoretically assure oneself that one holds to the Categorical Imperative in theory, but far messier in real life. If the study seeks to find out what we as German speakers report about these moral scenarios, then maybe there's something to be gained, but I would be very skeptical about whether or not this says anything about how we might morally act in the world.

familiar2: All of the examples that had to deal with sacrificing one life for many other lives to continue living. In philosophy, the outcome should always be that one life lost is tragic, but it would be better for only one life lost than many others. However, in the scenarios where others would be injured, but not killed by something, it is never morally right to kill one person to prevent others from being injured. These scenarios are tricky for me personally because I feel like I must do something, but I don't want to put others in harms' way.
